05080nam a22006135i 9780804780827DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20221995cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047808277 a10.1515/97808047808272doi  a(DE-B1597)582606  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aHIS0290002bisacsh00aIdentities in North America :bThe Search for Community /ced. by Robert L. Earle, John D. Wirth. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©1995  a1 online resource (268 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aComparative Studies in History, Institutions, and Public Policy00tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tContributors -- tIntroduction -- tPART I. CORE VALUES -- tCanada: Values in Search of a Vision -- tAmerican Identity: A Political Compact -- tApproaches to the Problem of Mexican Identity -- tPART TWO. Group Identities and Interactions -- tPluralism and Ecology in Canadian Cities -- tThe Dynamics of Assimilation in the United States -- tMexico: Culture and Identity in the Information Age -- tPART THREE. Regional Perspectives -- tQuebec in the Emerging North American Configuration -- tCascadia: The New BinationalismofWestern Canada and the U.S. Pacific Northwest -- tThe Gulf of Mexico: North America's Maritime Frontier -- tThe Mexico-U.S. Border: A Line of Paradox -- tConclusion: The Search for Community -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis is a wide-ranging inquiry into the forces that define the nations of North America and that, through convergence, are bringing North America's peoples and institutions closer together. These socio-cultural and regional forces form a web of factors that goes beyond trade and investment policy to articulate each nation's sense of identity through its history, values, and practices. Can some sort of functional community emerge from these disparate identities? Are there fresh opportunities for cooperation to be found in North America's value structures, social groupings, and institutions? If so, what are the costs and the benefits that might accompany interactions that touch upon each nation's culture and sense of self? Since no book at this early stage of continental consciousness can or should aspire to be definitive, this inquiry - by thirteen scholars from Canada, Mexico, and the United States - is an attempt to assess the dynamics of identities and to seek out ways in which the three nations can become more comfortable with their collective future on the continent. The book's underlying premise is not the inevitability of community in North America, but its possibility.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aPolitics -- International Relations. 7aHISTORY / North America.2bisacsh1 aBustamante, Jorge A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrombie, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEarle, Robert L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEarle, Robert L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEstrada, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamer, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKiy, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLatouche, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPachter, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRuy-Sanchez, Alberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchell, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpicer, Keith, econtributor.4ctb4https:/